"Rangel O.J.P., Silva C.A.","Carbon and nitrogen storage and organic fractions in latosol submitted to different use and management systems [Estoques de carbono e nitrogênio e frações orgânicas de latossolo submetido a diferentes sistemas de uso e manejo]",2007,"Revista Brasileira de Ciencia do Solo","31","6",,"1609","1623",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-41149169534&partnerID=40&md5=deb1f65ef1e9a42403e2291749659d29","Departamento de Ciencia do Solo, Universidade Federal de Lavras - UFLA, Caixa Postal 3037, CEP 37200-000 Lavras (MG), Brazil; Departamento de Ciência do Solo, UFLA","Rangel, O.J.P., Departamento de Ciencia do Solo, Universidade Federal de Lavras - UFLA, Caixa Postal 3037, CEP 37200-000 Lavras (MG), Brazil; Silva, C.A., Departamento de Ciência do Solo, UFLA","The advance of the agricultural frontier, characterized by the conversion of natural ecosystems into cultivated areas, was intensified in the last decades. Most of the practices used to manage soils cause changes in the soil quality and soil organic matter (SOM) dynamics. Studying the impact of different management systems is essential to choose the most adequate soil management practices. This study aimed to evaluate different SOM fractions and carbon and nitrogen storage of a very clayey typic dystroferric Red Latosol (Oxisol) under the following use and management systems: native forest (MTN), eucalyptus (EUC), pine (PIN), pasture (PAS), corn under minimum tillage (MCM) and corn under conventional till (MPC). The soil samples were collected in September 2004, in the 0-10, 10-20 and 20-40 cm layers to assess organic carbon (OC) and total nitrogen (TN) storage, in the 0-5 and 0-10 cm layers for the physical-densimetric SOM fractionation, and at 0-5 cm to measure the carbon content of the microbial biomass (Cmic). OC storage in the EUC soil was higher than in the MTN soil. The relative contribution of C increased in the order: C-clay &gt; C-silt &gt; C-sand &gt; CLF. The largest proportion (&gt; 90 %) of OC was associated to the heavy fraction of SOM, with values close to 98 % in the tillage systems with corn (MPC and MCM). The Cmic and C-light fraction (CLF) were more sensitive to evaluate changes in SOM dynamics caused by the different use and management systems of the studied Latosol.","Densimetric fractionation; Global climate change; Land use; Land-use change and forestry (LULUCF); Microbial biomass","Eucalyptus; Zea mays",,,,,,"ANDERSON, T.H., DOMSCH, K.H., Ratios of microbial biomass carbon to total organic matter in arable soils (1989) Soil Biol. Bioehem, 21, pp. 471-479; BATJES, N.H., (1999) Management options for reducing CO2- concentrations in the atmosphere by increasing carbon sequestration in the soil, , The Netherlands, ISRIC-Wageningen, 114p; BODDEY, R.M., ALVES, B.J.R., OLIVEIRA, O.C., URGUIGA, S., Potencial para acumulação e sequestro de carbono em pastagens de Brachiaria (2001) Mudanças climáticas globais e a agropecuária brasileira, pp. 213-229. , LIMA, M.A, CABRAL, O.M.R. & MIGUEZ, J.D.G, eds, Jaguariúna, Embrapa Meio Ambiente; BREMNER, J.M., Nitrogen total (1996) SSSA Book Series, 5 (PART 3), pp. 1085-1121. , SPARKS, D.L, ed. Methods of soil analysis. Madison, America Society of Agronomy; CAMARGO, F.A.C., GIANELLO, C., TEDESCO, M.J., VIDOR, C., Nitrogênio orgânico do solo (1999) Fundamentos da matéria orgânica do solo, pp. 117-137. , SANTOS, G.A. & CAMARGO, F.A.O, eds, Porto Alegre, Genesis; CHRISTENSEN, B.T. Organic matter in soil: Structure, function and turnover. In: PLANT production. Tjele, 2000. p. 95. (DIAS Report, 30)CHRISTENSEN, B.T., Physical fractionation of soil and organic matter in primary particle size and density separates (1992) Adv. Soil Sci, 20, pp. 1-90; COLLINS, H.P., PAUL, E.A., PAUSTIAN, K., ELLIOTT, E.T., Characterization of soil organic carbon relative to its stability and turnover (1997) Soil organic matter in temperate agroecossystems: Long-term experiments in North America, pp. 51-72. , P